<DOC><DOCNO> AP890816-0006 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0016EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-PTLChronology     08-16 0612</FIRST><SECOND>PM-PTL Chronology,0638</SECOND><HEAD>With PM-PTL Trial</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Here is a chronology of the major events involving PTL and JimBakker since his resignation as head of the Fort Mill, S.C.-basedministry and its Heritage USA Christian theme park:</TEXT><NOTE>1987</NOTE><TEXT>   March 19 _ Bakker resigns amid sex and money scandal involvingformer New York church secretary Jessica Hahn. The Rev. JerryFalwell takes over as chairman of the board and Richard Dortchbecomes president of PTL.   May 6 _ Assemblies of God leaders defrock Bakker and Dortch.   June 12 _ PTL files for protection from creditors under Chapter11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code.   Oct. 8 _ Falwell, the PTL board of directors, the co-hosts of the``PTL Show'' and other top executives resign from PTL during adispute over bankruptcy reorganization plan and fears that Bakkerwill be allowed to return. David Clark, a Christian BroadcastingNetwork executive, becomes trustee.   Dec. 22 _ U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds approves theministry's bankruptcy plan, which divides PTL into separateministerial and for-profit entities and involves a schedule forrepaying creditors.</TEXT><NOTE>1988</NOTE><TEXT>   Jan. 31 _ PTL sues Bakker and his chief aide, David Taggart, for$52 million for recovery of unwarranted compensation and funds lostthrough mismanagement.   April 22 _ The IRS revokes PTL's tax-exempt status.   May 20 _ Clark resigns as PTL trustee to become president ofHeritage Ministries, the non-profit ministerial entity. FormerWinston-Salem, N.C., Mayor M.C. Benton becomes the new trustee.Clark later resigns as president of Heritage Ministries.   June 7 _ Jim and Tammy Bakker return from California, open anoffice for Jim and Tammy Ministries and move into a condominium paidfor by supporters.   Aug. 31 _ Bakker and Benton agree on terms for Bakker to buyHeritage USA, paving the way for Bakker's return as leader of PTL.   Sept. 9 _ Bakker misses deadline for $3 million deposit. Bentonsays he will no longer negotiate with Bakker.   Nov. 3 _ U.S. Attorney Charles Alexander notifies the Bakkers andTaggart they are subjects of a grand jury investigation.   Nov. 10 _ Reynolds rules that the Bakkers and Taggart must pay$7.6 million in damages to PTL.   Dec. 5 _ Federal grand jury hands up indictments of Bakker andDortch on charges of mail fraud and wire fraud. They also areaccused of conspiring to defraud ministry contributors to supportextravagant lifestyles and of diverting more than $4 million in PTLmoney for their personal benefit. Bakker aides James and DavidTaggert are charged with evading taxes, conspiring to impede the IRSin tax collection, and using more than $1.1 million in PTL money forpersonal expenditures.   Dec. 13 _ Toronto real estate magnate Stephen Mernick, anOrthodox Jew, buys the assets of PTL for $65 million at a hearingbefore Judge Reynolds.</TEXT><NOTE>1989</NOTE><TEXT>   January _ The Bakkers begin broadcasting ``The Jim and TammyShow'' from their leased home in Charlotte.   Feb. 13 _ Mernick assumes joint management of the Heritage USAproperty with a bankruptcy trustee but title questions delay thesale's closing.   March 29 _ Bakker arrives at a Florida retreat for ministers, butcontinues to tape his program. Bakker had to cease his broadcastsfrom his Charlotte home since they violated zoning ordinances.   May 8 _ The Bakkers broadcast ``The Jim and Tammy Show'' livefrom their new studio in a boarded-up department store in a nearlyabandoned mall in southwest Orlando, Fla.   July 25 _ The Taggart brothers are convicted of tax evasioncharges.   Aug. 8 _ Dortch agrees to plead guilty four counts _ mail fraud,wire fraud by telephone, wire fraud by television and conspiracy _and testify against Bakker.</TEXT></DOC>